<DocsLayout title="HUMANFILE" description="The operator identity document. Tells the OS who you are and how you work.">
    <p class="lead">Your compiled identity. The OS reads this at boot and calibrates to you.</p>

    <h2>What it is</h2>
    <p>
      HUMANFILE is the document that tells the OS who you are, what models and secrets
      agents can use, and what drivers to load. Not a config file — a governance document.
      You write it once. Every agent that runs under your OS reads it.
    </p>
    <p>Location: <code>.ostk/HUMANFILE</code> in your project (project-level), or <code>~/.HUMANFILE</code> (global, shared across all projects).</p>

    <h2>Format</h2>
    <p>HUMANFILE uses a directive format: uppercase keywords, <code>#</code> comments, and <code>&lt;&lt;TAG</code> heredoc blocks for lists.</p>

    <h2>Example</h2>
    <pre><code># HUMANFILE — @yourname (Your Name &lt;you@example.com&gt;)

IDENTITY yourname
SIGN YOUR_GPG_FINGERPRINT_HERE

MODEL claude-sonnet-4-5
FALLBACK mistral-large-latest

AVAILABLE &lt;&lt;MODELS
claude-sonnet-4-5
claude-opus-4-6
claude-haiku-4-5
gemini-2.5-pro
gemini-3.1-pro
mistral-large-latest
codestral-latest
MODELS

SECRET &lt;&lt;KEYS
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY
GEMINI_API_KEY
OPENROUTER_API_KEY
KEYS

DRIVER fcp-rust
DRIVER fcp-screen
DRIVER fcp-web</code></pre>

    <h2>Directives</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Directive</th><th>Required</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>IDENTITY</code></td><td>Yes</td><td>Your username. Used in audit attribution and agent identity.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>SIGN</code></td><td>No</td><td>Your GPG key fingerprint. Establishes T0 trust tier when verified.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>MODEL</code></td><td>Yes</td><td>Default model for agent sessions. The kernel auto-detects provider from model name.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>FALLBACK</code></td><td>No</td><td>Model to use when the primary is unavailable or rate-limited.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>AVAILABLE &lt;&lt;MODELS</code></td><td>No</td><td>Heredoc block listing all models the OS is authorized to use. Used by <code>FROM auto</code> in Agentfiles.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>SECRET &lt;&lt;KEYS</code></td><td>No</td><td>Heredoc block listing API key names agents can access. Keys are stored in platform keychain via <code>ostk secret set</code> — never in the file itself.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>DRIVER</code></td><td>No</td><td>FCP device driver to load at boot. One per line. Standard drivers: <code>fcp-rust</code>, <code>fcp-screen</code>, <code>fcp-web</code>.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Secrets</h2>
    <p>
      The <code>SECRET</code> block is the only place where API keys are authorized for agent use.
      If a key isn't listed, agents cannot access it — even if it exists in your system keychain.
    </p>
    <p>The kernel resolves secrets in order:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>BYO secret manager</strong> — set <code>OSTK_SECRET_CMD</code> to your tool (bw, op, pass)</li>
      <li><strong>Platform keychain</strong> — <code>ostk secret set KEY</code> stores in platform keychain (macOS Keychain / Linux secret-tool)</li>
      <li><strong>Environment variable</strong> — fallback to <code>$KEY</code> in your shell env</li>
    </ol>
    <p>You only need the key(s) for your chosen provider:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><code>claude-*</code> → <code>ANTHROPIC_API_KEY</code></li>
      <li><code>gemini-*</code> → <code>GEMINI_API_KEY</code></li>
      <li><code>mistral-*</code> / <code>codestral-*</code> → <code>MISTRAL_API_KEY</code></li>
      <li><code>openrouter/*</code> → <code>OPENROUTER_API_KEY</code></li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The bail template</h2>
    <p>
      When you run <code>ostk init</code>, the OS downloads a governance bail from
      <a href="https://github.com/os-tack/ostk.ai">os-tack/ostk.ai</a> and personalizes
      the HUMANFILE template with your git identity and GPG key:
    </p>
    <pre><code># HUMANFILE — @&#123;USERNAME&#125; (&#123;OPERATOR&#125;)
#
# Your identity, secrets, and autonomy grants.
# Created by ostk init from os-tack/ostk.ai governance bail.
#
# Docs: https://ostk.ai/docs/humanfile

IDENTITY &#123;USERNAME&#125;
SIGN &#123;GPG_KEY&#125;

MODEL claude-sonnet-4-5

SECRET &lt;&lt;KEYS
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY
KEYS

DRIVER fcp-rust
DRIVER fcp-screen
DRIVER fcp-web</code></pre>
    <p>Placeholders (<code>&#123;USERNAME&#125;</code>, <code>&#123;GPG_KEY&#125;</code>) are replaced with values from your git config and GPG keyring.</p>

    <h2>GPG signing</h2>
    <p>
      Signing your HUMANFILE establishes T0 operator identity — the highest trust tier.
      Without a signature, the OS operates at T2 (named, unverified).
    </p>
    <pre><code>ostk sign</code></pre>
    <p>This signs the HUMANFILE with the GPG key specified in your <code>SIGN</code> directive. Alternatively:</p>
    <pre><code>gpg --armor --detach-sign .ostk/HUMANFILE</code></pre>
    <p>The signature file (<code>HUMANFILE.asc</code>) is read at boot alongside HUMANFILE.</p>

    <h2>Global vs project HUMANFILE</h2>
    <p>
      <code>~/.HUMANFILE</code> applies to all projects on your machine. <code>.ostk/HUMANFILE</code>
      is project-specific and takes precedence. The global file is created by <code>ostk init --guided</code>
      when you configure identity.
    </p>

